<tool id="SAGA.ta_lighting.5" name="Topographic Openness" version="1.0.0"><description>Topographic openness expresses the dominance (positive) or enclosure (negative) of a landscape location. See Yokoyama et al. (2002) for a precise definition. Openness has been related to how wide a landscape can be viewed from any position. It has been proven to be a meaningful input for computer aided geomorphological mapping. </description><inputs><param name="DEM" label="Elevation" help="Elevation" type="text" format="image/tiff, application/x-ogc-envi, application/x-ogc-aaigrid, image/png" /><param name="RADIUS" label="Radial Limit" help="Radial Limit" type="float" format="image/tiff, application/x-ogc-envi, application/x-ogc-aaigrid, image/png" /><param name="METHOD" label="Method" help="Method" type="text" format="image/tiff, application/x-ogc-envi, application/x-ogc-aaigrid, image/png" /><param name="DLEVEL" label="Multi Scale Factor" help="Multi Scale Factor" type="float" format="image/tiff, application/x-ogc-envi, application/x-ogc-aaigrid, image/png" /><param name="NDIRS" label="Number of Sectors" help="Number of Sectors" type="integer" format="image/tiff, application/x-ogc-envi, application/x-ogc-aaigrid, image/png" /></inputs><outputs><data name="POS" label="Positive Openness" /><data name="NEG" label="Negative Openness" /></outputs></tool>